objkt.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #132

metadata.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #132
metadata.description:
Experimental generative collection that merges analog photography, AI, generative text, and algorithmic coding, by digging down into the essence and building blocks of the different artistic communication channels. 

This work engages with all aforementioned mediums in a joint manner, guided by a random process. It starts with a collection of analog photographs, shot on film and scanned that were later used as a training dataset in Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) training. This way, A.I. learns the main characteristics of film photography. In particular, it mimics its recognizable grain. Another type of pixel grain is added with the use of code and pixel shifting as well as digital manipulation. Finally, the last type of “grain” appears with the use of generative text where a different kind of A.I. was given a short description of the project and instructed to imagine the rest of the story. The fragmented and void of meaning parts of generative text are added to the images as one of the possible traits.

metadata.name: Bellissimas #234
metadata.description:
Expressive portraits inspired by @michelepetrelli 

The used techniques search in the unexplored field of mixing pfp layer based work and real-time generative algorithms changing and adding to the premade assets.

The pre-generated assets include original artworks by Petrelli, Imitations of Petrelli's work by @brutalisti, GAN generated artworks inspired by Petrelli using several different AI technologies.

Every generatively chosen layer combination is live-processed and generatively altered in aspects of color and shape. Then the generative algorithm proceed with captured color palettes and generate background and additional drawing over and under the initial layers. The final result as acquired by visualizing everything with live generative algorithm that give additional layer of uniqueness.

Project by  @michelepetrelli & @brutalisti, curated by XCOLLABS

metadata.name: Proxima #139
metadata.description:
The preparations for the first mission began in 2142. It had become clear that mining petroleum on Earth would soon become financially unfeasible, so looking to other planets was the only logical choice. It took seventeen more years to perfect the technology so that the first colonists could reach Proxima b within the lifetime of one generation.

After 45 years of travelling at almost one-tenth of the speed of light, they reached their new home. It was rich in petrochemicals but scarce in the nutrients necessary for long term human survival. After merely six generations, humanity was forced to travel once again in search of a new world. The four missions that parted from the Proxima system to colonise other possibly habitable planets in the galaxy sparked a new age of human civilisation that would never see itself united and thriving again.

Eventually, all the colonies became independent societies as their differing interests drove them apart. Each small civilisation chose its path, wandering the void of space alone. Over time, millions of kilometres apart, each colony developed its own culture and traditions. While their habits and customs changed, some things remained the same across all the societies, like how it became a certain tradition to convert the outer world years and days to Earth time and celebrate holidays according to the calendar of the old world.

The new nomads learned from the first pilgrims. They used the technology once optimised for oil extraction to traverse other worlds, searching for sustenance. Peculiar wandering nonspaces emerged from the involuntary degrowth of human civilisation.

-----

Click on the image to open the menu. You may choose the quality from preview to the resolution of a print of approximately 30cm in height. In live mode, click on PNG to save the rendered image.
Depending on the device and CPU usage, it takes from a few seconds (on fast computers) to a minute (sometimes more) on mid-tier phones to render the image.

Requirements: 1GB of RAM. The system needs up to 200 MB of free RAM for rendering square preview images and up to 400 MB of free RAM for rendering square images at the highest resolution. We tested on Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge / Windows, Mac OS, Android, and iPhone, but please make sure it works on your device before minting.

Original piece by mrkswcz and Ismahelio. Made with Three.js. 

San Sebastian - Madrid. May 2022.

metadata.name: The beauty of imperfection #69
metadata.description:
Drawing shapes repeatedly, spinning and rotating. I use basic shapes like square, rectangle, and triangle to create this art. Regular shapes are perfect but it's a little bit boring, so I make them imperfect, just like "hand drawing". I also tried to make this generative art great for physical print, so that I can hang it on the wall. Here we go.

5 background colors:
Black, White, Blue, Green, and Red

Press “space” to play animation.
Press “s” to save.

Made with p5js.
Created by Costa C. | OneRocket.nft

metadata.description:
Hi! It's time to publish a collection of avatars for the fxhash community!!!
I've been thinking for a long time about what each fxhash user's avatar should look like. The pixel style is outdated. Animals are no longer interesting to use as an image.
But, every user is a programmer, designer and collector. We are all different! We love tech, we love art, we love uniqueness!
Welcome!

metadata.name: Mandatory Destiny #1
metadata.description:
"Mandatory Destiny" is the fifth collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

It is impossible for everyone to be equal. Too much of a person is defined by random chance. The country they were born in, the financial situation of their family, even their genetics. If someone was unlucky and has low natural IQ, they can't change it. And it affects their life significantly. If someone was born in a poor country or family, it might be extremely harder to get a good education, and later, a well-paying job. Some people are fortunate enough to get a headstart, while others aren't so lucky.

The only way for everyone to be truly equal would be identical starting conditions, and that's utterly impossible to achieve.

metadata.name: Mur #347
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: THE400FLIPS #335
metadata.description:
The more they flip. The more you’ll make.

p5.js –> Blockchain


Controls:

[s] save as PNG.
[a] render alternate higher resolution artwork (takes a few seconds).
[z] save alternate artwork as PNG.


Artist note:

Primary royalties are split 95-5% between artist and The Processing Foundation.

Secondary royalties go to the minters (99.9% of the 15%).

The preview thumbnails don’t do justice to the artworks. Please run the code to appreciate them better. Also, remember to check the alternate higher resolution renders using [a].

Some preview thumbnails might look slightly different to the artwork seen when running the code. This is due to the resolution difference between the capture module and the live code on your device. 

Please get in touch in the event of a blank preview thumbnail. 

Made in p5.js and rendered in webGL. Tested on Chrome and Safari.
